  <h1>How Whistleblower Awards Work</h1>
  <h2>The Core Mechanism</h2>
  <p>Congress created financial incentives for insiders to report fraud by awarding them a percentage of government recoveries. The theory: those with inside knowledge are best positioned to detect sophisticated fraud, and the prospect of a financial award outweighs the personal risk of coming forward.</p>
  <h2>Eligibility</h2>
  <p>You must: (1) voluntarily submit; (2) original information; (3) that leads to a successful enforcement action; (4) resulting in sanctions above the program threshold. "Original information" can come from independent knowledge or analysis — you don't need to be an employee of the violator.</p>
  <h2>How Awards Are Determined</h2>
  <p>Agencies have discretion within the statutory range. Positive factors include: tip significance, cooperation quality, and whether the information prompted a new investigation. Negative factors include: unreasonable delay, interference with compliance programs, and prior criminal history related to the violation.</p>
  <h2>Timeline</h2>
  <p>SEC cases average 4–7 years. IRS cases often take longer. Awards are paid after sanctions are collected — not when fines are imposed.</p>
  <h2>Tax Treatment</h2>
  <p>Whistleblower awards are generally taxable income. IRS awards are treated as ordinary income. SEC/CFTC awards may qualify for preferential treatment in some circumstances — consult a tax attorney.</p>
